- Sat 4 Jan 2020
CMRE (Comite Multisectoriel de la Riposte a la maladie a virus Ebola)
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us3.campaign-archive.com/?u= b34a30571d429859fb249533d&id= d6d90917d0&e=b8b1e1fcf3

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 3 Jan 2020:
- Since the start of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases has been 3386, of which 3268 have been confirmed and 118 are probable. In total, there were 2233 deaths (2115 confirmed and 118 probable) and 1114 people recovered;
- 523 suspected cases under investigation;
- 1 new confirmed case in North Kivu at Butembo;
- 1 new death from confirmed cases, including 1 death from confirmed cases in North Kivu in Katwa; no community deaths have been recorded;
- no cured persons have been released from Ebola treatment centers [ETCs];
- no health worker is among the new confirmed cases. The cumulative number of confirmed/probable cases among health workers is 164 (5% of all confirmed/probable cases), including 41 deaths;
The general coordinator of the response to the Ebola virus disease epidemic, Prof. Steve Ahuka Mundeke, intervened this Sat 4 Jan 2020 at the 28th ethics day of Kinshasa organized by the urban council of the Order of physicians (CUOM) under the theme "Medical ethics and ethics, the foundation of practice of the art of healing" in the Agora Amphitheater at Bel Campus University in Kinshasa;
- For Prof. Ahuka, there is a link between managing the epidemic and ethics in medical practice. The Ebola crisis, he said, concerns all health personnel, particularly doctors, recalling that doctors must intervene in this crisis while respecting the ethics as intended by this day;
- "There are many aspects of deontology and ethics in medical practice and in the management of Ebola. Lack of hospital hygiene is one of the major factors in the spread of the disease. To this is added the lack of prevention and control of infection in Congolese hospitals. This is an important element of which doctors must be aware, "said the general coordinator of the response during the 28th ethics day in Kinshasa;
- The intervention of the general coordinator of the response to the Ebola virus disease epidemic at these meetings focused on the communication on the current situation of the Ebola virus disease epidemic;
- This day ended with the presentation of a diploma of merit to a few doctors and pharmacists for their distinction and commitment to their profession. The diploma of Professor Jean-Jacques Muyembe Ntamfum was symbolically awarded to Prof. Ahuka.

News
Vaccination
-----------
- 4551 people were vaccinated, until 2 Dec 2019, with the 2nd vaccine Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN-Filo (Johnson & Johnson) in the 2 health areas from Karisimbi to Goma;
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018 with the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, 261 027 people have been vaccinated;
- Approved on 22 Oct 2019 by the Ethics Committee of the School of Public Health at the University of Kinshasa and on 23 Oct 2019 by the National Ethics Committee, the 2nd vaccine, called Ad26.ZEBOV/MVA-BN-Filo, is produced by the firm Janssen Pharmaceuticals for the company Johnson & Johnson;
- This new vaccine complements the 1st, rVSV-ZEBOV, a vaccine used until then (since 8 Aug 2018) in this epidemic manufactured by the pharmaceutical group Merck, after approval by the Ethics Committee on 20 May 2018. It was recently pre-qualified for certification.
Entry point surveillance
- Since the start of the epidemic, the cumulative number of travelers checked (temperature taken) at health checkpoints is 134 802 696;
- To date, a total of 109 entry points (PoE) and health control points (PoC) have been established in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri in order to protect the country's major cities and avoid the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

Monitoring at entry points
----------------------------
- Since the start of the epidemic, the cumulative number of travelers checked (temperature measurement) at health checkpoints is 134 802 696;
- To date, a total of 109 entry points (PoE) and health control points (PoC) have been established in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri in order to protect the country's major cities and avoid the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

