Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Scientists and clinicians have made great headway in developing the expertise to treat and protect against infection with Ebola. There are currently 2 vaccines in use in the DRC, the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine candidate (V920) administered in a single dose (Merck), now pre-qualified for certification, and the Ad26-ZEBOV/MVA-BN-Filo vaccine candidate administered in a prime-boost regimen (produced by the firm Janssen Pharmaceuticals for the company Johnson & Johnson. Antiviral therapies include ZMapp, a monoclonal antibody medication composed of 3 chimeric monoclonal antibodies that target the EBOV glycoprotein (Mapp Biopharmaceutical), REGN-EB3, a cocktail of 3 monoclonal Ebola antibodies made by Regeneron Pharmaceuticals, and mAb114, a single monoclonal antibody developed by the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, as well as 2 antiviral drugs, favipiravir and remdesivir (Gilead; GS-5734). In an ongoing clinical trial, Remdesivir and ZMapp have been dropped. Similarly, advances have been made in rapid diagnosis; OraQuick Ebola Rapid Antigen Test is the 1st rapid diagnostic test the FDA has allowed to be marketed in the U.S.

But such impressive scientific advances sadly are not proving sufficient in the case of Ebola, as an effective vaccine also is not in the case of measles as well as some other infectious diseases. In the DRC, social problems -- unrest, distrust -- are jeopardizing ending this current outbreak. The report above and the recommended reading referred to below explore how crucial the expertise of anthropologists is and how it can be applied to emergency public health responses. Certainly, as the authors in the paper state, successful responses to public health emergencies often, if not always, require collaboration between specialists such as clinicians, epidemiologists and social scientists.

See: D Stellmach, I Beshar, J Bedford et al. Anthropology in public health emergencies: what is anthropology good for? BMJ Glob Health. 2018; 3(2): e000534. Published online 2018 Mar 25. doi: 10.1136/bmjgh-2017-000534

Abstract. Recent outbreaks of Ebola virus disease (2013-2016) and Zika virus (2015-2016) bring renewed recognition of the need to understand social pathways of disease transmission and barriers to care. Social scientists, anthropologists in particular, have been recognised as important players in disease outbreak response because of their ability to assess social, economic and political factors in local contexts. However, in emergency public health response, as with any interdisciplinary setting, different professions may disagree over methods, ethics and the nature of evidence itself. A disease outbreak is no place to begin to negotiate disciplinary differences. Given increasing demand for anthropologists to work alongside epidemiologists, clinicians and public health professionals in health crises, this paper gives a basic introduction to anthropological methods and seeks to bridge the gap in disciplinary expectations within emergencies. It asks: "What can anthropologists do in a public health crisis and how do they do it?" It argues for an interdisciplinary conception of emergency and the recognition that social, psychological and institutional factors influence all aspects of care. - Mod.LK

Maps of Congo DR: http://goo.gl/DM2AT8 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6872195,194]
